default1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThree long term conditions are responsible for most cases of sight loss in the UK: age-related macular degeneration (AMD), diabetic retinopathy and glaucoma. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAMDdefault defaultis the biggest cause of sight loss in the UK.
default 
defaultA recent study estimated that 
default2.4% of people in the UK 
defaultaged 50
default 
defaultyears or more had advanced wet AMD, increasing to 4.8% of those aged 65
default 
defaultyears or more and 12.2% of those aged 80
default 
defaultyears or more
default.
default 
defaultSmokers are three times more likely to suffer AMD
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe following table shows how the number of people with advanced AMD is predicted to rise
default 
defaultby a third
default to 679,000 this decade
default (the middle line shows prevalence amongst women and the bottom line prevalence amongst men):
default1.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDiabetic retinopathydefault is the biggest cause of sight loss amongst pe
defaultople of working age in the UK.
default 
defaultIt occurs when diabetes weakens the blood vessels in the eye.
default 
defaultPeople with diabetes are 25 times more likely than the general population to become blind
default.
default 
defaultDiabetes UK estimates that by 2025 there will be 5 million people in
default England 
defaultwith diabetes
default and for each year someone lives with diabetes, their risk of retinopathy increases.
default&#xa0;
default1.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGlaucomadefault is estimated to affect about half a million people in England.
default 
defaultThe prevalence of glaucoma rises steeply with advancing age.
default 
defaultAfrican-Caribbean people are at particular risk.
default 
defaultMore than half of those glaucoma cases are thought to be undetected
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government is committed to reducing preventable sight loss from these three long term conditions through an indicator in its 
defaultPublic health outcomes framework
default.
default 
defaultWe strongly support this.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSight loss has a major impact on people’s well being.
default 
defaultSight is the sense people most fear losing.
default 
defaultOver one-third of older people with sight loss are also living with depression
default. Two-thirds of registered blind and partially sighted people of working age are not in paid employment
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople with a long term eye condition often have other health problems
default too
default.
default 
defaultSight loss is associated with a heightened risk of falls and fractures
default and people with a long term eye condition
default often have 
defaultother 
defaultlong term condition
defaults
default, such as dementia
default and diabetes.
default 
