default2.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur recent report, 
defaultBetter data, better care 
defaultshowed how the NHS’ reliance on paper forms for payment and referrals hindered care and wasted valuable time and resources in the fight to prevent sight loss from long term eye conditions
default.
default 
defaultThe failure to enable community and secondary care teams to share data is a major drag on the capacity of existing eye care services to meet demand now and in the future.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are examples of 
defaultinnovation, which
default if properly implement
defaulted
default across the NHS, 
defaultwould
default boost our capacity to meet the needs of people with long term eye conditions in the future.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTaking glaucoma care
default,
default for example, 
defaultNICE recommends that patients at risk of glaucoma be monitored in t
defaulthe community by optometrists th
defaultrough ‘repeat measures’ schemes
default rather
default than
default in hospitals
default.
default 
defaultMore advanced monitoring
default 
defaultin the community
default (referral refinement)
default is also recommended by the College of Optometrists and the Royal College of Ophthalmologists
default.
default 
defaultTogether, these schemes
default im
defaultprove 
defaultglaucoma 
defaultpatients’ access to quality care by increas
defaulting
default the capacity of eye services.
default 
defaultThey 
defaultkeep less serious cases out of hospitals and take advantage of thousands of community optometrists already performing sight test
defaults
default and 
defaultcaring for patients 
defaultin
default 
defaultthe NHS.
default 
defaultThey can also save significant amounts of money; NHS Evidence found that moving repeat measurement for glaucoma in 
defaultto 
defaultthe community 
defaultin Bexley 
defaultwas 62% cheaper than the equivalent hospital tariff
default. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo minimise sight loss from AMD, Gloucestershire has introduced a one stop shop model with integrated IT. Rather than assessing and treating patients over two visits, here assessment and treatment clinics run in parallel using non-consultant staff in particular nurse practitioners and optometrists. All clinical data is recorded electronically, allowing the consultant to make rapid treatment decisions for new and returning wet AMD patients using information on patient electronic medical records
default. 
default&#xa0;
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn most of England, we do not know the answer to simple questions like, how many patients are we
default treating for glaucoma or if at risk groups 
defaultget their eyes examined.
default 
defaultScotland has been particularly innovative 
defaultin
default overcoming IT barriers 
defaultby
default integrat
defaulting the electronic systems of
default community optometrists and hospitals eye unit 
defaultto
default 
defaultimprove access to 
defaultbetter 
defaultquality care and improve efficiency at the same time.
default 
defaultFollowing a successful pilot, the Scottish Government is committed to ensuring that 95% of referrals from community optometrists to hospitals are done elect
defaultronically rather than in paper.
default 
defaultPaper referrals are the 
defaultnorm in most of England.
default 
defaultMoving to e
defaultlectronic referral means community and hospital clinicians can share much more information about their patients over time with the aim 
defaultof
default improv
defaulting
default the continuity of care, reduc
defaulting
default unnecessary referrals to the hospitals, improv
defaulting
default efficiency and improv
defaulting
default patient outcomes.
default&#xa0;
default3.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultScotland is also working towards 
defaultmaking 
defaultprovider payment forms electronic
default.
default 
defaultElectronic payment facilitates much better data collection about who is accessing eye care and how to design services that improve the care of populations with long term eye conditions.
default 
defaultHowever, in England, most optometrists 
defaultmust submit their payment forms, 
defaultwhich include potentially valuable public health data, in paper form making it extremely difficult to analyse
default the data 
defaultto
default improve eye health services
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf accomplished, the Governments push for a paperless NHS offers great potential to improve eye care for people with long term conditions.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe move to involve clinicians more closely in commissioning also offers potential to improve care.
default 
defaultNHS England is introducing Local Eye Health Networks in to each local team area
default to bring together commissioners, community and hospital clinicians and patient groups to work together to assess local need and improve the quality and efficiency of eye health services for their local population.
default 
defaultWe strongly recommend that commissioners take advantage of these networks and are supporting our members so they can contribute fully.
